s to protester perspectives and interviews with South Korean officials and activists, this volume recasts the history of Korean division and draws a much more nuanced portrait of the region's Cold War legacies. The book ultimately helps readers conceive of the DMZ as a dynamic summation of personalized experiences rather than as a fixed site of historical significance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBorderlandsxSocial aspectszKorean Demilitarized Zone (Korea) 0aBorderlandsxSocial aspectszKorean Demilitarized Zone (Korea). 0aFamilieszKorean Demilitarized Zone (Korea) 0aFamilieszKorean Demilitarized Zone (Korea). 0aGroup identity - Korean Demilitarized Zone (Korea). 0aGroup identityzKorean Demilitarized Zone (Korea) 0aKoreansxEthnic identity. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kim-1648240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231537261/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK